body:
Hi, 
I'm developing a tox client that uses only audio calls. Chat and video calls are not supported. 
After the commit "Improve video key frame sending." (721358208b6650c62aa654be922867f10a5d6f38) in the log was displayed the message: "Invalid video packet: frame offset (0)> = full frame length (0)"
Why does that happen, I don't use video calls at all?

comment_data.body:
Bump!
Dear developers, I ask you to pay attention to this problem. I'm stuck on this issue and can not move on
Does this error cause any problems or is it just the log message?

Hi, @sudden6 
I have already started writing a lengthy letter describing when an error occurs, but then decided to rebuild the qTox (with it I'm testing) to the actual state. So I can say that the problem is almost solved. Almost - because the EchoBot still produces such a mistake. 
I took the EchoBot here: https://github.com/TokTok/py-toxcore-c
To me it's still not clear what the actual error is, only the log message?

@iphydf put those into rtp.c

https://github.com/TokTok/c-toxcore/blob/bd62d11860a4e6e540f7116f0ef6c56b28b18837/toxav/rtp.c#L470

i think this is wrong.
on old video packets both values are "0" so this will always be true i think
same goes for audio packets

also this seems wrong to me:

https://github.com/TokTok/c-toxcore/blob/bd62d11860a4e6e540f7116f0ef6c56b28b18837/toxav/rtp.c#L772

header.flags = RTP_LARGE_FRAME should only be set if session->payload_type is video.
there is a condition on the receiving side, but its still sort of wrong to set this on audio packets.
it'll haunt us some time in the future

> To me it's still not clear what the actual error is, only the log message?

Explanation: I updated toxcore to gitrev bd62d11860a4e6e540f7116f0ef6c56b28b18837. With this toxcore I built  qTox and my tox-client. When making a call to the qTox - I do not see any mistakes in the log of my tox-client.

> header.flags = RTP_LARGE_FRAME should only be set if session->payload_type is video.

How can I test an option without using large frames? 
The matter is that I now test the my tox-client. @Diadlo has kindly agreed to help me with it. We are faced with the problem of the periodic disgusting quality of audio communication. And this does not apply only to my tox-client, a bunch of qTox-qTox works bad too. The sound strongly jingles, no word can be understood. I assume that this may be due to packet loss. Perhaps reducing the size of the transmitted data frames would reduce this problem. In any case, I'm ready to experiment.
@hkarel is your client written in C ?

> @hkarel is your client written in C ?

C++ + Qt

@hkarel try to build a version with

https://github.com/zoff99/c-toxcore/tree/zoff99/_0.1.10_2017_video_fix_09

to see if your video and audio issues are fixed.
but use this **only for testing**!!! that toxcore version is bleeding edge stuff
@iphydf this is a critical bug i'll fix it tonight.
@zoff99 I with @hkarel have tested your branch with no effect. You can contact me in tox and we will try to reproduce

labels.description: Bug fix for the user, not a fix to a build script
